<!-- HERO -->
<section class="section text-white text-center" style="background-color: var(--primary-green);">
  <div class="container">
    <h1 class="display-5 fw-bold">About the Society</h1>
    <p class="lead mb-4" style="max-width: 700px; margin: 0 auto;">
      The Solar Energy Society of Nigeria (SESN) was founded in 1980 to promote the widespread utilization of solar and other renewable energy technologies across the country.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section">
  <div class="container">

    

    <!-- HISTORY SNAPSHOT -->
    <div class="card p-4 shadow-sm mb-4">
      <h5 class="fw-bold">Our Foundation</h5>
      <p class="text-muted">
        SESN was inaugurated in March 1980 at the Project Development Institute (PRODA), Enugu, and officially launched on 11th July 1980 by the Deputy Governor of the then Anambra State, Engr. A.S. Umenyi.
      </p>

      <p class="text-muted">
        Pioneer members included distinguished scholars such as Prof. A.O.E. Animalu (Foundation President), Prof. G.O. Ezekwe, Prof. C.C.O. Ezeilo, Prof. U.A. Akinsote, Prof. R.I. Salawu, Late Prof. N.I. Ngoka, and Prof. A.T. Sulaiman.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- NASEF -->
    <div class="card p-4 shadow-sm mb-4">
      <h5 class="fw-bold">National Solar Energy Forum (NASEF)</h5>
      <p class="text-muted">
        The Society organizes its annual National Solar Energy Forum (NASEF), providing a platform for stakeholders in research, development, business, and policy-making to interact and assess progress in renewable energy technologies across Nigeria.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- OBJECTIVES -->
    <div class="card p-4 shadow-sm mb-4">
      <h5 class="fw-bold">Objectives of the Society</h5>

      <ul class="text-muted">
        <li>Provide a forum for scientists, engineers, and stakeholders to discuss solar energy issues.</li>
        <li>Promote high standards in the study and application of solar energy.</li>
        <li>Advise government on solar energy development policies.</li>
        <li>Encourage research and training in solar energy applications.</li>
        <li>Facilitate membership in international organizations such as ISES.</li>
        <li>Disseminate knowledge through journals and newsletters.</li>
        <li>Support policies that advance renewable energy adoption.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- MEMBERSHIP -->
    <div class="card p-4 shadow-sm mb-4">
      <h5 class="fw-bold">Membership Categories</h5>

      <ul class="text-muted">
        <li>Fellowship (F)</li>
        <li>Full Membership (M)</li>
        <li>Associate Membership (AM)</li>
        <li>Student Membership (SM)</li>
        <li>Affiliate Membership (AFM)</li>
        <li>Institutional Membership (IM)</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- JOURNAL -->
    <div class="card p-4 shadow-sm">
      <h5 class="fw-bold">Nigeria Journal of Solar Energy (NJSE)</h5>

      <p class="text-muted">
        Since its inception, SESN has published the Nigeria Journal of Solar Energy (NJSE) annually. The journal serves as a platform for the dissemination of research findings and technical papers in energy science.
      </p>

      <ul class="text-muted">
        <li>Promotes collaboration among scientists and engineers.</li>
        <li>Publishes high-quality peer-reviewed research.</li>
        <li>Supports dissemination of conference papers from NASEF.</li>
      </ul>

      <p class="text-muted mt-3">
        Through advocacy efforts, SESN has contributed to policy development, including support for the Energy Commission of Nigeria and the establishment of research centres across the country.
      </p>
    </div>

  </div>
</section>